Additional Info: The most commonly reported flag from the period. Flags with green, white and red stripes also seem to have been used. Probably flown exclusively on ships. The Turkish flag was the official national flag.
Flown over the palace in Rabat and on ships. Military flags on land were often dectorated with a yellow or green octagram.

Arab monarchies, especially those in and around the Gulf, flew plain red flags from their ships. These weren't quite "national flags" in the modern sense, but European powers tended to view them that way.

Officially all of the Trucial States were supposed to fly a square red flag with a thick white border. In practice this flag became exclusively associated with the Al Qasimi dynasty. The other states mostly flew plain red flags.

Flown by exclusively by the sultan as a symbol of religious authority. Not really a "national flag" as we'd understand it in modern terms. The sultan also gave white flags to his vassal emirs within the Caliphate.

Flown by private citizens and merchant ships. The "Italian Social Republic", the Nazi puppet regime in the north, flew the plain tricolour as a national flag and had a war flag with an eagle gripping a fasces. The anti-fascist Italian partisans flew either plain tricolours or tricolours with a white or red star on the middle stripe.
Flown by the government and navy.
The dynastic colours of the Hapsburg monarchy, often used as a flag on land.
Flown by navy ships. Direct predecessor of the modern Austrian flag.
Flag of the federal army, treated as an unofficial national flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the royal house, the government, and the armed forces. Also granted to a select list of private institutions and companies.
Allowed to be flown by anyone. The union mark in the top-left corner of the flag was flown on its own as a joint diplomatic flag for Sweden and Norway.
Flown only on state-owned buildings and naval ships.
Allowed to be flown by anyone. The union mark in the top-left corner of the flag was flown on its own as a joint diplomatic flag for Sweden and Norway.
Flown on government buildings and by the military.
Flown on land within Greece. The military flag had a crown in the centre of the cross.
Flown at sea and abroad. The naval ensign had a crown in the centre of the cross.
Flown by the prince, and unofficially as a national flag.
Flown unofficially, mostly by civilian ships.
The flag of the Emperor, often regarded as the Russian national flag during the period.
Flown on government buildings, especially military buildings, and as patriotic decoration.
Designated as the official colours of the Austrian crown land of Carniola. Regarded as the unofficial national flag of Slovenia.
Flown by advocates of Slovakian independence. The "Upper Hungary" region did not have an official flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown the government and armed forces.
Flown by Ukrainian nationalists. The order of colours wasn't fixed.

Designated as the official colours of the Austrian crown land of Bohemia. Not an official flag, but informally regarded as a Czech national symbol. A white flag with the Bohemian coat of arms was also sometimes used.
Flown by the prince and the military.
The former royal banner of Poland, no longer official but still used as an informal national symbol.

A typical flag flown by Bulgarian nationalists and revolutionaries in the pre-independence period. The flag would sometimes have different inscriptions or colours, but a golden lion on green was a common element. The slogan here reads "Freedom or Death!"
The maharaja's flag had yellow stripes at the top and bottom.
Flown by the Maharao and also used as a state flag. The flag was sometimes much longer.
The reverse side of the flag showed a moon and a flower.
Mewar had a number of reported princely banners which were also sometimes used as state flags. The most common one had a large yellow sun and a blue katar dagger.
Kolhapur flew the Maratha saffron banner as a state flag. The maharaja had a diagonally-divided red and orange flag.
Flag of the maharaja, also used as a state flag. Plain saffron flags were also sometimes flown.
Flown by the maharaja and often used as a state flag.
Allowed to be flown by civilians.
Inland river boats flew a triangular pennant in the same colours.
The Raja's flag had a red sun
Flown by naval ships. The merchant flag was red with a yellow circle.
Malay monarchs often flew plain white flags. These standards eventually evolved into individual state flags as more colours and symbols were added.
Flown by the sultan and by naval ships.
Flown by commoner merchants at sea.
Flown by the sultan and also used as an unofficial state flag.
Flown by the sultan and on naval ships.
Flown by merchant ships and sometimes used by civilians as an alternate national flag.
Reported flag from this era. It's exact use isn't known.
Officially only flown on government ships, but often used as a national flag.
The former flag of the United Tribes of New Zealand, which remained in use as an unofficial symbol of the country.
An unofficial but widespread national flag.
An unofficial local flag. The British colony of Newfoundland had no distinctive local symbols.
Flown by the government, the navy, the national police, and national sports teams. Raised at major ceremonies. The army uses a similar flag with a different coat of arms.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
The most common Costa Rican flag. Officially designated for private citizens, but in practice often used on government buildings and schools too.
Flown by the government and by diplomatic missions, although also used sometimes by private citizens.
Flown by Cuban nationalists and revolutionaries who sought independence from Spain.
Flown by Puerto Rican nationalists and revolutionaries who sought independence from Spain.
Flown by the government and armed forces.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the government and armed forces, and unofficially used by many private citizens.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the maharaja and often used as a state flag. The swallowtailed saffron Maratha banner was also sometimes flown.
Flag of the Opalchentsi, the Bulgarian volunteer army units that fought in the Russo-Turkish War. This was the direct predecessor of the Bulgarian national flag.
The previous plain red flag was sometimes flown as an alternate state flag.
There was also a red British colonial ensign with the coat of arms on it.
The nawab's flag, which was sometimes used as an alternate state flag, was white with a green hand.
The maharaja's flag had a gold eagle on it. The armed forces used a flag with white and purple stripes.
The raja's flag had a gold tiger head in the middle. The war flag was a red flag with the state coat of arms on it.
The maharawat's flag had the same design but in yellow instead of white.
The flag flown at the palace had the state coat of arms on it.
The begum's standard had a crown and inscription on it.
Flown the government and armed forces.
Unofficial flag of the merchant fleet.
A typical flag flown by Albanian nationalists. The exact design of the eagle was not fixed.
Flown by the merchant fleet. The plain Serbian tricolour was also widely flown within in the country.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown over the Prince's Palace and government buildings.
Flown by the merchant fleet. The plain Serbian tricolour was also widely flown within in the country.
Flown the government and armed forces.
Flown by the government and by naval ships. The merchant flag was red with a yellow circle.
Flown by the governmnent. The armed forces flew a similar flag with olive and laurel branches around the coat of arms.
Flag of the maharaja's dynasty, used as a state flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by Puerto Rican nationalists and revolutionaries who sought independence from Spain.
Flown on government buildings. The military continued flying the old three-tailed war flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone. The naval and war flags still had the Swden-Norway union mark in the top-left corner.
Flown only on state-owned buildings and naval ships.

A typical example of a Moro battle flag. No two were exactly alike, but they all looked roughly like this. Sometimes the daggers were crossed, or the crescent and star was replaced by a white and blue emblem.
Officially only to be flown civilian ships, but in practice flown widely on land as the national flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown on government buildings. The military continued flying the old three-tailed war flag.
Flown by the king and the government.
Flown by the government and armed forces, and unofficially used by many private citizens.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.

The "Calcutta flag" flown by independence activists. British India had several colonial flags. A red civil ensign with the Star of India medal on it was used to represent India at international sporting events.
Flag of the All-India Muslim League, which advocated for Muslim interests within British India. The direct predecessor of the flag of Pakistan.
The most common Costa Rican flag. Officially designated for private citizens, but in practice often used on government buildings and schools too.
Flown by the government and by diplomatic missions, although also used sometimes by private citizens.
Flown by the government, and often by private citizens.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.

Officially only to be flown civilian ships, but in practice flown widely on land as the national flag. The badge was only supposed to have the arms of the original four provinces, but the nine-province version was much more common. It was also often placed on a white disc, or adorned with wreath of maple leaves and a crown.
The number of points could vary. Some flags even had a completely straight-edged stripe.
Flown over the sultan's palace and the military.
The most common flag, flown over most government buildings, at ceremonies, by diplomatic missions and often by public citizens.
An alternative government flag, most commonly flown by the armed forces but also on some public buildings and offices.
The simplest version of the national flag, flown by some private citizens.
There were many variations of this flag, depending on who was flying it and when. Some versions would have added inscriptions, decorations or royal symbols. The flag could also be triangular.
A symbol of the Imperial house permitted for use by private citizens. Relatively uncommon, mostly used on decorative or propaganda images.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown on government buildings and coast guard ships.
Flown by Sinhalese nationalists in Ceylon, now Sri Lanka. There was also an infrequently-used blue British colonial ensign with an elephant badge.
Flown by the government and naval ships.
Flown by the government and armed forces. Flown on a temporary basis while the current national flag was being designed.
Allowed to be flown by anyone. Mostly used by merchant ships. Flown on a temporary basis while the current national flag was being designed.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the government, border guard, and public universities. The armed forces fly a version with a swallowtail cut.
The flag preferred by supporters of Catalan independence.
Flown by the Russian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic during the Russian Civil War.
Flown by the Latvian Socialist Soviet Republic, the government of the Bolshevik-occupied areas of Latvia during the Russian Civil War.
Flown by the Commune of the Working People of Estonia, the government of the Bolshevik-occupied areas of Estonia during the Russian Civil War.
Flown by the Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic, the government of the Bolshevik-occupied areas of Lithuania during the Russian Civil War.
Unofficial flag of the merchant fleet.
Flown by the breakaway Republic of East Karelia, which aimed for independence from Russia and integration with Finland.
One of the possible reported flags of the Karakorum-Altai government, also known as the Confederated Republic of Altai.
Flown by the federal government and the armed forces.
Flown by the Ukrainian Socialist Soviet Republic, the government of the Bolshevik-occupied areas of Ukraine during the Russian Civil War.
Flown by the breakaway Republic of North Ingria, which aimed for independence from Russia and integration with Finland.
Flown by the Korean independence movement and the unrecognized government-in-exile based in China. Banned under Japanese occupation.
In Palestine, flown unofficially by the Arab community. Merchant ships flew a red British ensign with a badge that said "PALESTINE". The Jewish community flew the modern flag of Israel.
Flown by the Jewish community in the British mandate of Palestine. Direct ancestor of the flag of Israel.
Flown by the government, border guard, and public universities. The armed forces fly a version with a swallowtail cut.
Flown by the Armenian Socialist Soviet Republic, the governmnet of the Bolshevik-occupied areas in Armenia during the Russian Civil War.
There was also a colonial "protectorate flag" which was plain yellow with a French tricolour in the top left corner.

The Svaraj ("self-rule") flag flown by nationalists and independence activists. British India had several colonial flags. A red civil ensign with the Star of India medal on it was used to represent India at international sporting events and in the League of Nations.
Flown by the Nationalist government in Guangzhou, which controlled Southern China.
Flag of the Syrian Federation, a union of three French-administered statelets under a League of Nations mandate.
Part of the Soviet Union, which did not yet have a national flag.
Flown by the President and on state-owned ships.
Flown by Indonesian nationalists. The Dutch East Indies did not have an official national flag.
Officially only to be flown civilian ships, but in practice flown widely on land as the national flag.
The state flag was sometimes used without the emblem. Inland river boats flew a triangular pennant in the same colours.
There was also a red colonial British ensign with a black tower and a white crescent and star.
Flown by the governmnent. The armed forces flew a similar flag with olive and laurel branches around the coat of arms.
Flown by nationalists and indepenence activists. The French colony in Algeria did not have an official flag.
Flown by merchant ships to avoid confusion with the maritime signal flag for "H"
Flown by Indonesian nationalists but banned by Dutch colonial authorities. The Dutch East Indies did not have an official national flag.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the royal house, the government, the armed forces, and diplomatic missions.
Flown by the government and armed forces, and unofficially used by many private citizens.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.

State Name: Abu Dhabi · Dubai · Ajman ·  Umm al-Quwain

Additional Info: The Svaraj ("self-rule") flag flown by nationalists and independence activists. British India had several colonial flags. A red civil ensign with the Star of India medal on it was used to represent India at international sporting events and in the League of Nations.
Often (but not always) flown by the royal house and the government.
Flown by the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria. Most countries did not recognize its independence.
Flown by the government, and often by private citizens. At sea, and in certain ceremonial settings on land, the ratio was :.
Allowed to be flown by anyone. At sea, the ratio was :.
The design of the flag wasn't laid down in law, and this may have been one of many variations in use at the time.
The flag of the Nazi Party, flown alongside the tricolour as a co-national flag. On land, the swastika was often centred instead of shifted to one side.
The Uyghur nationalist flag. Xinjiang Province did not have an official flag.
Flown by the federal government and the armed forces.
The most common Costa Rican flag. Officially designated for private citizens, but in practice often used on government buildings and schools too.
Flown by the government and by diplomatic missions, although also used sometimes by private citizens.
Flown by the nationalist Thakins, who sought the independence of Burma. The British colonial government did not have a distinct flag.
Flown by Karen nationalists seeking independence and separation from Burma.
The design of the flag wasn't laid down in law, and this may have been one of many variations in use at the time.
Flown by the rebel Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War.
The maharaja's flag was red with yellow stripes at the top and bottom.
Flown by the maharaja and often used as a state flag. The swallowtailed saffron Maratha banner was also sometimes flown. There was a red colonial British ensign with a scimitar and horseman badge.
Flag of the maharaja, also sometimes used as a state flag.
Flown by merchant ships operating out of the Spanish zone in northern Morocco. The Moroccan national flag was flown on land.
Flown by the rebel Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the royal house and the government.
Flag flown by the Free French Forces and the government-in-exile. The plain tricolour was still seen as the national flag.
Flown by the Korean independence movement and the unrecognized government-in-exile based in China. Banned under Japanese occupation.
Flown unofficially, mostly by civilian ships. Plain flags without the George Cross were also common. The colonial government had a blue ensign with the Maltese coat of arms on it.
The flag of the anti-Japanese resistance.
Flown by the federal government and the armed forces.

Flown by German ships, but explicitly not as a national flag, and not given any of the ceremonial respect typically given to national flags. Not used on land. Known as the "C-Pennant" since it was derived for the maritime signal flag for the letter C.
There was also a red colonial British ensign with a black tower and a white crescent and star.
Sarawak also had a blue colonial ensign.
Flown in the Pakistan-controlled parts of the disputed region of Kashmir.
Flag of the Convention People's Party, which sought independence from Great Britain. Direct predecessor of the flag of Ghana. The colony also had a rarely-used British ensign with an elephant badge.
There was apparently only a single physical version of this flag ever made.

The flag of the Republic of China, the government of Taiwan. Banned on the mainland, as the People's Republic of China claimed sovereignty over the island. Regarded as the flag of China at the United Nations.
Flown by the United Issarak Front, a communist resistance movement which claimed to be the independent government of Cambodia.
Flown by the government, the navy, the national police, and national sports teams. Raised at major ceremonies. The army uses a similar flag with a different coat of arms.
Flag of the Kenya African Union, which sought independence from Great Britain. Direct predecessor of the modern flag of Kenya. The colony also had a rarely-used British ensign with a red lion badge.
Flown in the Indian-controlled parts of the disputed region of Kashmir.
A traditional military emblem, ceremonially flown alongside the national flag at government buildings.

Flag Name: flag of the Treinta y Tres
Additional Info: A historic flag, ceremonially flown alongside the national flag at government buildings.

Flag of the Nyasaland African Congress, which sought independence from Great Britain. Direct predecessor of the flag of Malawi. The colony was part of the nominally self-governing Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, which had a rarely-used British ensign with the federation coat of arms.
Often flown alongside the national flag.
Flown by the government, sporting teams and by some private citizens. More or less exclusively a unionist symbol.

Flag of the Tanganyika African National Union, which sought independence from Great Britain. Direct predecessor of the  flag of Tanganyika, and by extension the flag of Tanzania. The colony also had a rarely-used British ensign with a giraffe badge.
Flown by the government and armed forces, and unofficially used by many private citizens.
Flown by embassies, airports, and merchant ships. Private use strictly banned.
Flown by nationalists and separatists. The Naga Hills area did not have an official flag within India.
Not legally the national flag, but allowed to be flown wherever a "distinctive Canadian flag" was needed.

Flag of the United National Independence Party, which sought independence for the British colony of Northern Rhodesia. Direct predecessor of the modern flag of Zambia. The colony was part of the nominally self-governing Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, which had a rarely-used British ensign with the federation coat of arms.
Flag of the Federation of South Arabia, the British protected state at the core of South Arabia.
Flag of the South West Africa People's Organisation, which sought independence from South Africa. Direct predecessor of the flag of Namibia. The territorial government did not have an official flag.

Flag of the African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde, which aimed for separation from Portugal. Eventually became the flag of Guinea-Bissau. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.
Flag of the National Democratic Union of Mozambique, which aimed for independence from Portugal. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.

Flag of the Zimbabwe African People's Union, which sought independence and majority rule for the British colony of Southern Rhodesia. The colony was part of the nominally self-governing Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, which had a rarely-used British ensign with the federation coat of arms.
Flag of the Liberation Front of Mozambique, which aimed for independence from Portugal. Direct predecessor of the modern flag of Mozambique. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.
Flag of the National Liberation Front of Angola, which aimed for independence from Portugal, and its government-in-exile in Léopoldville. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.
Flown unofficially, mostly at sporting events

Flag of the Zimbabwe African National Union, which sought independence and majority rule for the British colony of Southern Rhodesia. The colony was part of the nominally self-governing Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, which had a rarely-used British ensign with the federation coat of arms.
Flag of the National Liberation Front, which sought independence from Great Britain. Direct predecessor of the flag of South Yemen.
Flag of People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola, a competing independence movement. Direct predecessor of the modern Angolan flag.
Flown by the government, and often by private citizens. In certain ceremonial settings, the ratio was :.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the government and by diplomatic missions, although also used sometimes by private citizens.
The popular but unofficial flag of the Kannada people. The Indian state of Karnataka does not have an official flag.
Flag of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, yet another independence movement.
The unofficial but popular cultural flag of the island.
An unofficial flag flown by Martinican nationalists and occasionally by local municipalities.

Flag of the Viet Cong. Flown by the communist Provisional Revolutionary Government of the Republic of South Vietnam, which claimed to be the legitimate government of South Vietnam and was recognized by most Eastern Bloc states.
During the rule of the junta, the shade of blue on the national flag was described as notably darker.
Flag of the Movement for the Liberation of São Tomé and Príncipe, which aimed for independence from Portugal. Direct predecessor of the modern flag. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.

Flag of the Front for the Liberation of the Somali Coast, which sought indepdence from France. Eventually became the flag of Djibouti. The French Territory of the Afars and the Issas did not have an official flag.
Flown by the Federation of Arab Republics. Its member states sometimes distinguished their flags by adding their country's name in small gold writing below the emblem.
Flag of the Oromo Liberation Front, a nationalist liberation movement within Ethiopia. Oromia did not have an official flag within Ethiopia at this time.

Flown by the Popular Front for the Liberation of Saguia el-Hamra and Río de Oro, which sought indepdence from Spain. The Spanish Sahara colony had no official flag, but ships registered there did fly a blue and yellow pennant.
Flag of the Revolutionary Front for an Independent East Timor, which aimed for separation from Portugal. Portuguese colonies did not have official flags.

Flag of the Tigray People's Liberation Front, a nationalist liberation movement within Ethiopia. Direct predecessor of the modern regional flag. Tigray did not have an official flag within Ethiopia at this time.

Flown by nationalists seeking the indpenedence of Timor-Leste. Under Indonesian occupation, flying the flag was illegal. The rarely-used official flag of "Timor Timur" was orange with the provincial seal in the middle.
Flown by the breakaway Republic of North Solomons, which tried to win independence from the newly-formed Papua New Guinea.
Flag of the Eritrean Liberation Front, which sought independence from Ethiopia. Direct predecessor of the modern flag. The provincial government did not have an official flag.

Flown by the Vanua'aku Pati and the People's Provisional Government, which pushed for the independence of what would become Vanuatu. The Anglo-French condominium in the New Hebrides did not have an official flag.
Flown by the government, border guard, and public universities. The armed forces fly a version with a swallowtail cut.
Flown by the departmental council and used as a local flag.

Flown by Baloch nationalists seeking independence from Pakistan, Iran, and Afghanistan. The star is sometimes flipped upside down or replaced by a white sun. The provincial government of Balochistan in Pakistan flies a green flag with a white camel emblem.
A popular but unofficial local flag.
Flag of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement, which sought independence for the southern part of Sudan. Direct predecessor of the modern flag. The region did not have an official flag within Sudan.
Flown by the Chagossians, who were forcibly removed from the islands by the British to make way for a military base.
Flag of the Kanak and Socialist National Liberation Front, which sought the independence from France.
An unofficial flag flown by Guadeloupe nationalists. There is also a rarely used "heraldic banner" based on the coat of arms of Pointe-à-Pitre.
Flag of the Afghan Interim Government in Pakistan, flown by mujahideen fighters within the country.
Flag of the Afghan Interim Government in Pakistan, flown by mujahideen fighters within the country.
Flown by the State of Cambodia, the partially-recognized state in control of Phnom Penh.
The back side of the flag was just a plain tricolour.
A common cultural flag representing both the French and Dutch halves of the island of Saint Martin.
The plain tricolour has no legal status but is still flown unofficially.
The hammer and sickle was only on the front side of the flag.
The hammer and sickle was only on the front side of the flag.
The hammer and sickle was only on the front side of the flag.
The hammer and sickle was only on the front side of the flag.
Flown by Abdul Rashid Dostum's proto-state in Mazar-i-Sharif.
Flown by the United Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia, which briefly controlled Cambodia and oversaw elections after the end of the Third Indochina War.
Some versions of the flag have the ring of stars extending over all three stripes.
Flag of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement, which sought independence for the southern part of Sudan. Direct predecessor of the modern flag. The region did not have an official flag within Sudan.
The plain tricolour is still flown unofficially.
Flag of the unrecognized Taliban regime in control of Kabul.
Flag of the unrecognized Taliban regime in control of Kabul.
Flown by the government and by diplomatic missions, although also used sometimes by private citizens.
The official flag of the British overseas territory, flown by the government and allowed to be flown by anyone.
A popular but unofficial local flag flown by some municipalities.

Flown by the republic government, and by local and provincial governments on national holidays and days of mourning. Allowed to be used by private citizens during celebrations, sporting events, and any other context that isn't expressly forbidden by law. In other words, it can basically be used anyone at any time.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Ceremonial flag, flown at the Royal Palace in Vilnius, Trakai Island Castle, and War Museum in Kaunas. Also flown over government buildings on certain holidays.
Flown by the governmnent. The armed forces fly a similar flag with olive and laurel branches around the coat of arms.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.
Flown by the government and armed forces, and unofficially used by many private citizens.
Allowed to be flown by anyone.

Flown by the national government, and by local and provincial governments on national holidays and days of mourning. Allowed to be used by private citizens during celebrations, sporting events, and any other context that isn't expressly forbidden by law. In other words, it can basically be used anyone at any time.
Flown by protestors against the Assad regime and in areas by controlled by the Syrian National Council
Flown by the departmental council and used as a local flag.
Designated for use at international cultural or sporting events.
Flown by the largely-unrecognized Taliban government
